:INFO
Bookbinding Tools Worth Owning
You can start with almost nothing, but a few specific tools make binding faster, more precise, and more satisfying. This page covers what each tool does and when to buy it.

:CHECKLIST
Essential Tools
[ ] Bone folder — scores, folds, creases; plastic or teflon for coated papers
[ ] Bookbinding needles — blunt tip, large eye, available in packs
[ ] Waxed linen thread — 18/3 or 25/3 weight for most projects
[ ] Awl — for piercing holes in signatures; a bradawl also works
[ ] PVA glue — flexible when dry, archival quality

:CHECKLIST
Useful but Not Immediately Required
[ ] Bone paper knife — separates and tears paper cleanly
[ ] Microspatula — manipulates glued pages without tearing
[ ] Book press or binder clips — holds glued sections while drying
[ ] Cutting mat and metal ruler for accurate trimming
[ ] Davey board (bookbinder's board) for hardcover case binding

:NOTE
PVA vs. Paste vs. Methyl Cellulose
PVA (polyvinyl acetate) is the standard bookbinding adhesive — flexible, strong, and archival. Wheat starch paste dries slower and is more reversible, preferred for restoration work. Methyl cellulose is used as a sizing and for attaching Japanese tissue paper repairs. For basic binding, PVA alone covers 95% of needs.

:PATH
Where to Source Materials
Online suppliers have the best selection — art stores carry only basics.
|
:INFO
Where to Source Materials
Talas (talasonline.com) and Hollander's carry the full range of bookbinding supplies including specialty papers, boards, and adhesives. Amazon carries basic needles and thread. Local art stores may have bone folders and cutting mats. Japanese papers for endpapers and covering are best sourced from specialty paper suppliers.
